# Networking Secure Protocols

**Room:** [TryHackMe – Networking Secure Protocols](https://tryhackme.com/room/networkingsecureprotocols)
**Status:** Completed

## Summary
Covered the encrypted counterparts of common cleartext protocols —
SFTP, FTPS, SMTPS, POP3S, IMAPS, and SSH — and how they map to their
insecure equivalents via TLS/SSL.

## Cleartext → Secure Port Mapping
| Cleartext Protocol | Port | Secure Protocol | Port |
|---|---|---|---|
| FTP | 21 | FTPS | 990 |
| Telnet/SSH (control) | 23 | SSH | 22 |
| SMTP | 25 | SMTPS | 587 |
| POP3 | 110 | POP3S | 995 |
| IMAP | 143 | IMAPS | 993 |

## Key Concepts
- **SFTP** runs over the SSH protocol suite (port 22), not a separate
  encryption layer — commands like `get filename` / `put filename`
  mirror FTP but ride inside an SSH session
- **FTPS** secures FTP using TLS certificates, typically on port 990,
  and requires separate control/data channel handling — trickier to
  pass through strict firewalls than SFTP

